\begin_layout Subsection*
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This policy mandates a lifecycle approach to identifying,
 assessing,
 responding to,
 and monitoring risks that threaten the confidentiality,
 integrity,
 and availability of County information systems.
 It serves as the authority for risk-based decision-making,
 resource prioritization,
 and the formal acceptance of operational risk.
 The Authorize step of the RMF lifecycle is operationalized through 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Security Control Assessment and Authorization),
 which consumes the risk ratings,
 security categorizations,
 and Corrective Action Plan status produced under this policy to render formal authorization decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.1 Risk Management Framework (RMF) Adoption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Information Operations Department adopts the NIST Risk Management Framework (RMF) as the strategic methodology for managing system lifecycles.
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure that all County information systems move through the RMF stages:
 Prepare,
 Categorize,
 Select,
 Implement,
 Assess,
 Authorize,
 and Monitor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Risk Management Strategy
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall maintain a documented Risk Management Strategy that defines risk appetite and tolerance,
 prioritization criteria,
 management decision rules for selecting risk responses,
 scoring methodology,
 reporting thresholds,
 and review cadence.
 The IT Director shall approve the Risk Management Strategy at least annually (NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 PM-9 (Risk Management Strategy)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Continuous Monitoring
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall align operational risk management with the NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF) 2.0 functions and shall integrate risk monitoring into the Department's Continuous Monitoring program.
 The Assistant IT Director shall record outputs as evidence in the Risk Register and control assessment records.
 The program shall explicitly track:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Effectiveness
\series default
:
 Monitoring ensuring security controls are operating as intended.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Compliance
\series default
:
 Monitoring ensuring adherence to CJIS,
 HIPAA,
 PCI,
 and County policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Change
\series default
:
 Monitoring identifying changes to systems or environments that alter the risk profile.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.2 Security Categorization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Assistant IT Director shall categorize all County information systems based on the potential impact of a loss of confidentiality,
 integrity,
 or availability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Authorizing Official Approval
\series default
:
 The IT Director (AO) shall review and formally approve the security categorization of all information systems (NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 RA-2 (Security Categorization)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Documentation
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall document security categorization results and rationale in the System Security Plan (SSP) or equivalent system security documentation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Criminal Justice Information (CJI)
\series default
:
 All systems processing,
 storing,
 or transmitting CJI shall be categorized,
 at a minimum,
 as Moderate Impact and shall implement CJIS-required controls and County controls commensurate with that impact level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Categorization Review
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall review security categorizations annually or following any significant system change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.3 Risk Assessment Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Assistant IT Director shall ensure that risk assessments identify threats,
 vulnerabilities,
 likelihood,
 and impact specific to the system environment.
 Assessments shall utilize the standardized scoring criteria defined in the Risk Management Strategy.
 Assessments shall explicitly consider supply chain risks in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Supply Chain Risk Management (SCRM) and Vendor Governance).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Assessment Cadence
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Quarterly Review
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall review all risk assessments at least quarterly.
 Review consists of Risk Register reconciliation,
 status validation,
 and treatment progress confirmation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Annual Update
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall perform formal risk assessment updates — including re-scoring and threat refresh — at least annually for non-critical systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
CJI and Critical Systems Update
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall perform formal risk assessment updates at least quarterly for CJI and Critical systems (CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section RA-3 (Risk Assessment)).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Event-Driven Reviews
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall initiate a risk assessment update within five (5) business days following any security incident,
 material system change,
 significant control failure,
 or confirmed vulnerability affecting County systems (NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 RA-3 (Risk Assessment)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Policy Review
\series default
:
 This policy shall be reviewed at least annually in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and updated when changes to the risk environment,
 regulatory requirements,
 or organizational structure warrant revision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Threat Intelligence
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall incorporate cyber threat intelligence received from external information-sharing forums (e.g.,
 MS-ISAC,
 FBI InfraGard) into the risk assessment process (NIST CSF 2.0:
 ID.RA-02 (Cyber Threat Intelligence)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.4 Vulnerability Monitoring and Remediation Standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Department shall employ automated tools to scan for vulnerabilities in information systems and hosted applications.
 Operational patching procedures,
 specific tool configurations,
 and authoritative remediation timelines are maintained in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Vulnerability and Patch Management Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Scope
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrators and Network Administrators shall scan internal assets,
 external perimeter assets,
 and web applications.
 Privileged vulnerability scans shall require explicit authorization from the IT Director or Assistant IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Scanning Frequency
\series default
:
 The responsible Administrators shall perform vulnerability scans at least monthly (County Baseline) and whenever new vulnerabilities potentially affecting the system are identified and reported,
 including following major configuration changes and critical exploit advisories (CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section RA-5 (Vulnerability Monitoring and Scanning)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Remediation
\series default
:
 The responsible Administrators shall remediate vulnerabilities within the timelines defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Severity ratings shall be based on the County-approved scoring standard (e.g.,
 CVSS base score or vendor severity,
 whichever is higher),
 as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Enforcement
\series default
:
 When remediation will exceed the timelines defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.09"
